@kevinburke You can use the [`ToSocketAddrs`](https://static.rust-lang.org/doc/master/std/net/trait.ToSocketAddrs.html) trait with a dummy port number like this:

``` rust
use std::net::ToSocketAddrs;
use std::io;

fn resolve(host: &str) -> io::Result<Vec<IpAddr>> {
    (s, 0).to_socket_addrs().map(|iter| iter.map(|socket_address| socket_address.ip()).collect())
}
```

… but this API does not support timeouts.

A 6-years old closed issue is not a great place for new discussion as it’s unlikely to get the attention it needs. That said, for all of its flaws, today’s `ToSocketAddrs` is also implemented for `(&str, u16)` which skips the concatenate-with-colon then split-at-colon dance:

```rust
use std::net::ToSocketAddrs;

let addresses: Vec<_> = ("rust-lang.org", 443).to_socket_addrs()?.collect();
dbg!(addresses);
```

This and other impls are documented at https://doc.rust-lang.org/std/net/trait.ToSocketAddrs.html
